<font face=Arial,Helvetica size=2>
<b>Reauthorization of the Violence Against Women Act of 1994</b><br><font face=Arial,Helvetica size=2> Posted on  Wednesday, August 02 @ 12:52:45 CDT

</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td bgcolor=ffffff>
<font face=Arial,Helvetica>
<a href=search.php3?query=&topic=31&author=><img src=images/topics/news.gif border=0 Alt="News" align=right hspace=10 vspace=10></a>
NATIONAL -- Last month both the Senate and House Judiciary Committees 
agreed on legislation to reauthorize the Violence Against Women Act of 
1994 (VAWA). The Senate Committee reached an agreement on new 
legislation (S. 2787) that would continue existing VAWA programs and 
create several new initiatives, including transitional housing for 
victims, a pilot program to reduce violence during children's visits and 
stronger protections for elderly, disabled and immigrant women. The 
legislation would authorize spending $645 million per year over the next 
five years. The House Committee agreed on legislation (H.R. 1248) that 
would renew VAWA funding for domestic violence programs. The House bill 
also includes new amendments that would create a task force to 
coordinate domestic violence research, target funds for disabled women, 
have the Justice Department create a national standard for rape kits and 
genetic sampling, and add domestic violence records to electronic 
records checked for gun purchases. Floor votes by the full House or 
Senate have not yet been scheduled, and may not occur until the fall.
<P>"Reprinted and adapted from <a href=redirect.php3?op=redir&sid=3&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.fvpf.org%2Fnewsflash>News 
Flash</a>, an online newsletter of the 
Family Violence Prevention Fund." <br><br>

</td>
